text: So a decentralized exchange is just anywhere you can swap one crypto asset for another. I guess you have NFT exchanges too, but we'll just talk about tokens, fungible tokens. So I have USDC and I want to use that to buy some Ethereum because I belong to Ethereum or vice versa. I want to sell Ethereum. So it's a single place on the blockchain, a smart contract that operates autonomously. So there's no venue. You don't have to deposit your money at FTX and hope that FTX has your money at the end of the day. It's still your key, still your crypto. Go trade it. You do a transaction. Tokens go out of your wallet. Tokens come back to your wallet at the end of the day. So it's very convenient in the sense that if I'm already holding assets on the blockchain, I just have to send a transaction through Metamask or whatever my wallet is. And now I have an exchange. I don't have to deposit. I don't have to hope that FTX still has my money or anything like that. That's the purpose of it. Now, the question is, how do you actually do that on the blockchain itself? Computational environment, way, way, way more limited than what NASDAQ can do on a big server. So the problem is, at least in Ethereum or Ethereum-like blockchains, order books don't really work. They're just not efficient. If you wanted to do one, the gas costs would get very high very quick. And there's all kinds of other practical issues. So order books don't work. So most are almost all decentralized exchanges. They're just are what's called an automated market maker. And it's a pretty ingenious design. At its core, it's pretty simple. There's a pool of liquidity providers. They put in 50% of one asset and 50% of the other asset. And then anyone who wants to swap those deposits, some assets on one side, and then is allowed to take out assets on the other. And every swap slightly moves the price. And the pool is always trying to stay balanced 50-50. So that's how the mechanics work. And math is actually pretty simple. There are variations to it, notably like concentrated liquidity, where you can provide liquidity over a given price range, which is more capital efficient. Probably Ethereum is not going to wick down to $10 in the next 10 minutes. So it's kind of inefficient to be depositing tokens. So someone can go trade Ethereum down to $10. It's not going to wick up to a million. So you can do concentrated liquidity. But the core idea is still simple. You just have a pool of liquidity providers who are getting paid swap fees to always kind of be on the market. And then you have the other side of these swaps. And hopefully the swap fees that they're getting paid might be 0.3% or whatever. It depends on the pool. The swap fees that they're getting paid hopefully compensates them for being on the other side of which way people want to trade. So the biggest difference between that and an order book is in order book, everyone's competing to provide liquidity, which creates a very PVP dynamic. Like I talked about all the Q stuff, all those other things. Some liquidity providers make way more money than other liquidity providers. Yeah. So it's more cooperative form of providing liquidity.
